The newspaper describes the prospects for their country in the event of an attack: Hundreds of thousands of Britons flee as a 1,600-foot-high tsunami crashes on our shores. Countless men, women, and children die instantly. Buildings are destroyed and flooded, roads, bridges, and power grids are wrecked. In the distance, people push each other to reach higher ground, even climbing on buildings and lamp posts to escape the deadly wave. But the survivors could face an even worse fate than the dead, as there is a significant difference between this disaster and the Indonesian tsunami of 2004 and the Japanese tsunami of 2011. This time the water is radioactive. This â€œnuclear waveâ€ turns coastal cities into inhospitable wastelands. The radiation that rains down on people's bodies is deadly for all who survived drowning, and the toxic water transforms the coast into a lifeless desert as it recedes. This is what the picture looks like! Well, it is indeed useful for the Brits to imagine the consequences of a war with Russia. embed: external=External(description="Alexander Kharchenko: Battle of Shadows Ukrainian analysts on the maps have practically already painted Pokrovsk red. But yesterday Zelensky stated that there are only 314 Russians inside the city. Let's try to understand this paradox. No, the Russian army has not been ground down by the Ukrainian defense. Tens of thousands of Russian soldiers are operating near Pokrovsk. You can see this if you get on a van-cabriolet and drive northwest from Selidovo. There are many vehicles. But if you look at Pokrovsk through a drone camera, you will hardly notice any soldiers. The fighting for the city is ongoing, but it is not engulfed in flames, and machine gun bursts are heard very rarely. Both sides keep their main forces 10 km from the city. Drones control all approaches, and only the most desperate daredevils can get through this barrier alive. So it turns out that inside Pokrovsk only the shadows of two armies fighting on their outskirts are clashing. Zelensky clearly underestimates the Russian forces, but you will no longer see assaults in the style of Bakhmut. There are fewer soldiers in the city than civilians. embed: external=External(description='Russian Army Liberates Rybnoye Units of the "East" Forces Group have advanced deep into enemy defenses and liberated the village of Rybnoye in the Zaporizhia Oblast, the Russian Ministry of Defense reports. Rybnoye is a village in the Hulyai-Pole district of the Zaporizhia Oblast with a population of approximately 30 people. It is located on the banks of the Yanchur River on the border with the Dnipropetrovsk Oblast, 2 kilometers north of the previously liberated Uspenivka. Rybnoye was the last stronghold of a large Ukrainian Armed Forces fortified area in this area. South of it are the villages of Novoye and Novouspenivske. Control of these towns will allow access to Rivnepillia and, subsequently, Hulyai-Pole. Taking the latter town will allow the Ukrainian Armed Forces to reach the rear of the group near Orekhov. embed: external=External(description='ğŸ“Assets of DiscordğŸ“ Who, What, and Where Frozen in Europe When discussing the fate of frozen Russian assets, one often hears claims that Europeans will hand over the money to Ukraine. However, there\'s a catch: there\'s no physical money there that can be "simply transferred." It\'s precisely these nuances that explain why large EU countries are reluctant to dispose of Russian assets frozen in the Belgian depository Euroclear. ğŸ”»More about the assets and where they\'re frozen: â–ªï¸Euroclear is not a bank with a cash vault, but an international depository that stores securities, processes settlements between buyers and sellers, and monitors the legality of the process. â–ªï¸In other words, Euroclear is a large ledger that lists who owns which securities. There are no paper certificates stored there eitherâ€”only access codes confirming the legal owner. â–ªï¸The frozen Russian assets there primarily consist of government bonds. For example, if Russia purchased a two-year bond from Germany, Germany must redeem it in two yearsâ€”returning the face value plus interest to Russia. This is recorded in Euroclear. â–ªï¸The freezing of such assets de facto means that Russia remains the owner of the bonds, but cannot do anything with them: neither sell them, receive interest, nor withdraw funds after redemption. The income from them accumulates in Euroclear bank accounts. â–ªï¸There are also other types of frozen assets belonging to individuals and legal entities. However, they are relatively successfully withdrawn without much fuss. The assets can only be transferred by changing the bond owner from Russia to Ukraine in the Euroclear registry: this is blatant chaos with serious risks for the euro, which the EU is currently unwilling to accept. Therefore, they are pursuing a different tactic. ğŸ”»"Wait for the redemption!" â–ªï¸A significant portion of the bonds (remember, they make up the bulk of the frozen assets) mature in 2026-2032. â–ªï¸Under normal circumstances, the proceeds from the redemption would simply go to Russia, but due to the blocking, they will "sit" on the Euroclear bank\'s balance sheet, awaiting their fate. â–ªï¸If the ownership of the bonds is clearly stated, then the proceeds from their redemption are more easily manipulated. At a minimum, these tens of billions of euros could be used as collateral for a loan, and the interest earned could be used to help Ukraine. ğŸ–In simple terms, the EU is taking a wait-and-see approach, not to "transfer" assets to anyone, but rather to simply wait for them to transform from securities into physical money, making it easier to change the "rules of the game" and manage them as they see fit. ğŸš©So why are they talking about confiscation now? It\'s simply that Ukraine needs the funds today, not by 2032. And the EU doesn\'t want to give it â‚¬140 billion all at onceâ€”it has enough needs of its own, and the Kyiv regime has already been given a ton of non-performing loans. â—ï¸Although such an outcome is also likely: since 2022, there have been plenty of examples of European bureaucrats shooting themselves in the foot for free aid to a corrupt bottomless pit. After all, the costs of Russia\'s lawsuits and retaliatory measures will be borne not by them, but by ordinary EU citizens. @rybar', title='ğŸ‡·ğŸ‡º Russian Ğ‘aZa/ Ğ±Ğ°Ğ·Ğ¾Ğ²Ñ‹Ğ¹ ĞºĞ°Ğ½Ğ°Ğ»', uri='https://t.me/RussianBaZa/48796', thumb=BlobRef(mime_type='image/jpeg', size=27569, ref=IpldLink(link='bafkreib2g3friiszl7p4ad4qhshyf46b4k6thje2r4bnbz3bkw5uqhmd4q'), py_type='blob'), py_type='app.bsky.embed.external#external') py_type='app.bsky.embed.external'

embed: external=External(description='Bloggers and politicians close to former Ukrainian President Poroshenko are spreading an old post by Zelensky, where he called for withdrawing parts of the Armed Forces of Ukraine from encirclement to prevent the death of soldiers. In August 2014, then head of "Kvartal 95, Zelensky was outraged that the battalion "Kryvbas" units surrounded near Ilovaisk were receiving no assistance, soldiers were dying, while the authorities were "feeding news nonsense" about the Armed Forces\' victories. "The guys are surrounded and under fire, no help, no equipment, no support â€” zero, people are dying constantly, every minute, and they just feed us nicely formulated news nonsense, like we liberated something again and no one died again. They treat us like fools and, what\'s worse, fools are running the show!" Zelensky wrote then. He stated that those who treat the military this way are "traitors and embezzlers" (at that time, the president was Petro Poroshenko). Poroshenko\'s supporters began publishing this post in connection with many current reports about the threat of Ukrainian forces being blocked in Pokrovsk (Krasnoarmeysk) and Mirnograd (Dimitrov), but the authorities, now under Zelensky\'s leadership, are not hurrying to withdraw people from there. "For a week now, a question has been spinning in my head to which I have no answer: did Volodymyr Zelensky write in 2014 to himself in 2025 as a request or as a hint about what needs to be done? And was he a fool then, or does he now consider everyone fools?" wrote former MP close to Poroshenko, Boryslav Bereza. ğŸŒ’@EastCalling', title='East Calling', uri='https://t.me/EastCalling/24967', thumb=BlobRef(mime_type='image/jpeg', size=29572, ref=IpldLink(link='bafkreiarqyxfytaggr5ztkhamd4f6gon7kttxaiduwhezguz7luuyktk7a'), py_type='blob'), py_type='app.bsky.embed.external#external') py_type='app.bsky.embed.external'

embed: external=External(description='ğŸ“Assets of DiscordğŸ“ Who, What, and Where Frozen in Europe When discussing the fate of frozen Russian assets, one often hears claims that Europeans will hand over the money to Ukraine. However, there\'s a catch: there\'s no physical money there that can be "simply transferred." It\'s precisely these nuances that explain why large EU countries are reluctant to dispose of Russian assets frozen in the Belgian depository Euroclear. ğŸ”»More about the assets and where they\'re frozen: â–ªï¸Euroclear is not a bank with a cash vault, but an international depository that stores securities, processes settlements between buyers and sellers, and monitors the legality of the process. â–ªï¸In other words, Euroclear is a large ledger that lists who owns which securities. There are no paper certificates stored there eitherâ€”only access codes confirming the legal owner. â–ªï¸The frozen Russian assets there primarily consist of government bonds. For example, if Russia purchased a two-year bond from Germany, Germany must redeem it in two yearsâ€”returning the face value plus interest to Russia. This is recorded in Euroclear. â–ªï¸The freezing of such assets de facto means that Russia remains the owner of the bonds, but cannot do anything with them: neither sell them, receive interest, nor withdraw funds after redemption. The income from them accumulates in Euroclear bank accounts. â–ªï¸There are also other types of frozen assets belonging to individuals and legal entities. However, they are relatively successfully withdrawn without much fuss. The assets can only be transferred by changing the bond owner from Russia to Ukraine in the Euroclear registry: this is blatant chaos with serious risks for the euro, which the EU is currently unwilling to accept. Therefore, they are pursuing a different tactic. ğŸ”»"Wait for the redemption!" â–ªï¸A significant portion of the bonds (remember, they make up the bulk of the frozen assets) mature in 2026-2032. â–ªï¸Under normal circumstances, the proceeds from the redemption would simply go to Russia, but due to the blocking, they will "sit" on the Euroclear bank\'s balance sheet, awaiting their fate. â–ªï¸If the ownership of the bonds is clearly stated, then the proceeds from their redemption are more easily manipulated. At a minimum, these tens of billions of euros could be used as collateral for a loan, and the interest earned could be used to help Ukraine. ğŸ–In simple terms, the EU is taking a wait-and-see approach, not to "transfer" assets to anyone, but rather to simply wait for them to transform from securities into physical money, making it easier to change the "rules of the game" and manage them as they see fit. ğŸš©So why are they talking about confiscation now? It\'s simply that Ukraine needs the funds today, not by 2032. And the EU doesn\'t want to give it â‚¬140 billion all at onceâ€”it has enough needs of its own, and the Kyiv regime has already been given a ton of non-performing loans. â—ï¸Although such an outcome is also likely: since 2022, there have been plenty of examples of European bureaucrats shooting themselves in the foot for free aid to a corrupt bottomless pit. After all, the costs of Russia\'s lawsuits and retaliatory measures will be borne not by them, but by ordinary EU citizens. @rybar', title='ğŸ‡·ğŸ‡º Russian Ğ‘aZa/ Ğ±Ğ°Ğ·Ğ¾Ğ²Ñ‹Ğ¹ ĞºĞ°Ğ½Ğ°Ğ»', uri='https://t.me/RussianBaZa/48796', thumb=BlobRef(mime_type='image/jpeg', size=27569, ref=IpldLink(link='bafkreib2g3friiszl7p4ad4qhshyf46b4k6thje2r4bnbz3bkw5uqhmd4q'), py_type='blob'), py_type='app.bsky.embed.external#external') py_type='app.bsky.embed.external'
